Alternatively, after reading with fgets, I can check for the newline and remove it by setting that character to '\0'. So steps in code:

Declare a buffer, say, char input[1024]; 

Read with fgets(input, sizeof(input), stdin);

Then, process the string: loop through each character in input. For each, if the char is ',', replace with ' '. Then print the string. Wait, but the buffer should be big enough.

Also, in the Java code, there's no limit except that the BufferedReader reads a line, which in practice is up to the system's default buffer. But for competition code, assuming the input is within, let's say 1000 characters, so using a buffer of 1024. So now, code steps:

#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

int main() {
    char input[1024];
    fgets(input, sizeof(input), stdin);
    // remove the trailing newline if present
    size_t len = strlen(input); if (len > 0 && input[len-1] == '\n') {
        input[len-1] = '\0';
        len--;
    }
    // replace commas with spaces
    for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {
        if (input[i] == ',') {
            input[i] = ' ';
        }
    }
    printf("%s\n", input);
    return 0;
} Hmm, that should work. Let's test this logic.

